## Comparison — All 3 Ordinal Approaches

| Approach | Order Based On | Risk |
|---|---|---|
| **Manual** `{'S':0,'M':1,'L':2}` | Your assumption | Wrong if assumption bad |
| **Label Encoding** | Alphabetical | Random, no meaning |
| **Target Guided** | Actual target data | Data-driven ✅ |

---

## When to Use

```
✅ High cardinality columns (many cities, zip codes)
✅ When category clearly impacts target
✅ Better than OHE when categories are 10+
❌ Don't use on test data alone → always fit on train data only!
```

---

## Train/Test Safe Version

```python
# Fit only on TRAIN data
mean_target = X_train.groupby('City')['Salary'].mean()
ordinal_map = mean_target.rank().to_dict()

# Apply to BOTH train and test
X_train['City_enc'] = X_train['City'].map(ordinal_map)
X_test['City_enc']  = X_test['City'].map(ordinal_map)

# Handle unseen cities in test data
X_test['City_enc'].fillna(X_test['City_enc'].median(), inplace=True)
```

This prevents **data leakage** — one of the most common ML mistakes! 🚨
